# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emo-trade-show
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emo-trade-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] The **Association for Manufacturing Technology** (**AMT**) is a trade association based in McLean, Virginia, in the United States.
[src:emo-trade-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] It was founded as the National Machine Tool Builders' Association (NMTBA) in 1902.
[src:emo-trade-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] It represents and promotes the interests of American providers of manufacturing machinery and equipment.
[src:emo-trade-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] As machine tools advanced, NMTBA launched the first National Machine Tool Builders’ Exposition in 1927, which would later be rebranded IMTS- International Manufacturing Technology Show.
[src:emo-trade-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] The AMT’s most visible activity is its management of the International Manufacturing Technology Show (IMTS), which is held on even-numbered years at McCormick Place in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:emo-trade-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] AMT also supports their membership with technology centers and representative offices in China, India, Poland, Mexico and Brazil.
[src:emo-trade-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] AMT puts on a number of events throughout the year.
[src:emo-trade-show/association-for-manufacturing-technology] While IMTS takes place in every even year, AMT also hosts the MFG Meeting and MTForecast Conference every year.
[src:emo-trade-show/emo-trade-show] The name *EMO* came from the name Exposition Mondiale de la Machine-Outil (Machine Tool World Exposition), and the scope of the content still reflects the machine tool heritage, although it now also extends beyond it.
[src:emo-trade-show/emo-trade-show] The show covers the spectrum of metalworking technologies, such as machine tools for milling, turning, and forming; manufacturing systems; precision measuring tools; automated materials handling; computer technology; industrial electronics; and accessories.
[src:emo-trade-show/emo-trade-show] EMO is run by CECIMO, the European Association of the Machine Tool Industries (Comité européen de coopération des industries de la machine-outil) (www.cecimo.eu).
[src:emo-trade-show/emo-trade-show] EMO began as the EEMO (Exposition européenne de machines-outils, European machine tools exhibition).
[src:emo-trade-show/emo-trade-show] The name changed in 1975 to EMO (Exposition Mondiale de la Machine-Outil).
[src:emo-trade-show/emo-trade-show] Nowadays its scope extends beyond machine tools, and the acronym expansion is not used by CECIMO anymore.
[src:emo-trade-show/fiera-milano] The company started operation on 1 October 2000 and has been listed on Borsa Italiana (STAR segment) since 12 December 2002.
[src:emo-trade-show/fiera-milano] Fiera Milano mainly operates in the fields of management and organisation of exhibitions, trade fairs and conferences.
[src:emo-trade-show/fiera-milano] It hosts about seventy shows (of which about one-third are directly organized) and 30,000 exhibitors every year.
[src:emo-trade-show/fiera-milano] It was involved in the Expo 2015 which took place around the grounds of the Fiera Milano Rho.
[src:emo-trade-show/fiera-milano] The Fiera Milano Rho complex was announced as the new speed skating venue of the 2026 Winter Olympics on 19 April 2023 after initial plans to put a roof over Ice Rink Piné had been rejected by the IOC.
[src:emo-trade-show/fiera-milano] The event was hosted at Halls 13 and 15, from which a single space was created to house a speed skating rink, with seating for 6,500.
[src:emo-trade-show/fiera-milano] The venue also hosted the secondary ice hockey rink.
[src:emo-trade-show/fiera-milano] The Fiera Milano City location mostly houses consumer trade shows such as the Milan Fashion Week.
[src:emo-trade-show/forming-metalworking] In metalworking, **forming** is the fashioning of metal parts and objects through mechanical deformation; the workpiece is reshaped without adding or removing material, and its mass remains unchanged.
[src:emo-trade-show/forming-metalworking] Forming operates on the materials science principle of plastic deformation, where the physical shape of a material is permanently deformed.
[src:emo-trade-show/forming-metalworking] Metal forming tends to have more uniform characteristics across its subprocesses than its contemporary processes, cutting and joining.
[src:emo-trade-show/forming-metalworking] Forming processes tend to be categorised by differences in effective stresses.
[src:emo-trade-show/forming-metalworking] These categories and descriptions are highly simplified, since the stresses operating at a local level in any given process are very complex and may involve many varieties of stresses operating simultaneously, or it may involve stresses which change over the course of the operation.
[src:emo-trade-show/forming-metalworking] This category of forming processes involves those operations where the primary means of plastic deformation involves both tensile stresses and compressive loads.
[src:emo-trade-show/forming-metalworking] This category of forming processes involves those operations where the primary means of plastic deformation is a bending load.
[src:emo-trade-show/forming-metalworking] This category of forming processes involves those operations where the primary means of plastic deformation is a shearing load.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] The **Hanover Fairground** (German: *Messegelände Hannover*) is an exhibition area in the *Mittelfeld* district of Hanover, Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] Featuring 392,453 m2 (4.2 million sq.ft.) of covered indoor space, 58,000 m2 (624,306 sq ft) of open-air space, 24 halls and pavilions, and a convention center with 35 function rooms, it is the largest exhibition ground in the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] The area of the fairground originally was an aircraft works.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] After World War II, the British military government in Allied-occupied Germany wanted to hold a trade fair and sought for a good place, since Leipzig, the traditional fairground of Germany, was unavailable, being in the Soviet occupation zone.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] The hangars in Laatzen, south of Hanover, were deemed suitable for this purpose, and so the Hanover Fair, then named *Exportmesse 1947* was first held in 1947 to promote the economic recovery in the Bizone.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] The concept proved to be successful, and so a permanent fairground was established, growing over the years.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] The Hermesturm (Hermes Tower) is a tower built of two concrete tubes on the fairground.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] The building was constructed between 1956 and 1958.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] Its total height, including the antenna, is 88.8 m, an observation deck at 65 m can be reached with an elevator.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] The fairground has been linked to the city's tramway network since 1949.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] The original terminus, called *Messegelände*, has been moved several times, the last time in 1982, when the line was upgraded to become part of the Hanover Stadtbahn, and is now situated at the entrance *Nord 2*, between halls 1 and 18.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] Service to the city centre is provided by the regular line **8** as well as the peak line **18**.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] During the large fairs, like CeBIT or Hannover Messe, there is a special peak hour express service, denoted by the letter **E**, which only stops at the stations Hauptbahnhof, Kröpcke and Aegidientorplatz.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] By employing highly efficient dispatching methods, trains can run in intervals as little as 90 seconds, each train able up to carry as many as 700 passengers.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] For the Expo 2000, a new line was built that connects the fairground to the *Kronsberg* city borough.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] It is currently served by the line **6**.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] When there are fairs or other large-scale events on the fairground, the additional line **16** increases the number of services.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] As soon as the line was completed, the old terminus at Hall 1 was renamed to *EXPO/Nord* whilst the new terminus carried the name of *EXPO/Ost*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] After the Expo, the terminuses were renamed to *Messe/Nord* (lines 8 and 18) and *Messe/Ost* (lines 6 and 16) respectively.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] In the 1960s, a railway station was built near the halls, however this was soon found to be impractical, as the station was constructed as a terminal of a branch line, making connections to and from main line trains difficult.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] However, it found its uses for dedicated services to the fairground.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] For the Expo 2000, an entirely new railway station was constructed some 500 metres west of the fairground on the Hanoverian Southern Railway and the Hanover–Würzburg high-speed railway.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] It is linked by the Skywalk, a people mover that works like a horizontal escalator.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] The railway station is named *Hannover Messe/Laatzen* after the suburb of Laatzen, which has a common border with Hanover near the fairground.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] It is only notably used during CeBIT, Hannover Messe and Agritechnica, and outside of this period, only regional services stop at the station.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-fairground] Since December 2008 the station has been connected to the Hanover S-Bahn, the city's suburban railway system.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] From 1714 to 1837 Hanover was by personal union the family seat of the Hanoverian Kings of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, under their title of the dukes of Brunswick-Lüneburg (later described as the Elector of Hanover).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The city lies at the confluence of the River Leine and its tributary the Ihme, in the south of the North German Plain.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The city is a major crossing point of railway lines and motorways (Autobahnen), connecting European main lines in both the east–west (Berlin–Ruhr area/Düsseldorf/Cologne) and north–south (Hamburg–Frankfurt/Stuttgart/Munich) directions.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover Airport lies north of the city, in Langenhagen, and is Germany's ninth-busiest airport.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The city's most notable institutes of higher education are the Hanover Medical School (*Medizinische Hochschule Hannover*), one of Germany's leading medical schools, with its university hospital *Klinikum der Medizinischen Hochschule Hannover*, and the Leibniz University Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The city is also home to International Neuroscience Institute.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Hanover Fairground, owing to numerous extensions, especially for the Expo 2000, is the largest in the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover hosts annual commercial trade fairs such as the Hanover Fair and up to 2018 the CeBIT.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It also hosts the biannual IAA Commercial Vehicles show, the world's leading trade show for transport, logistics and mobility.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Every year Hanover hosts the Schützenfest Hanover, the world's largest marksmen's festival, and the Oktoberfest Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 2014, Hanover was named a UNESCO City of Music, joining UNESCO's Creative Cities Network.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The name of the city may derive from the German *(am) hohen Ufer*, literally 'on the high (river) bank'.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Traditionally, the English spelling is ⟨*Hanover*⟩.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] However, ⟨*Hannover*⟩, the German spelling with a double-⟨n⟩, has become more popular in English.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Recent editions of Encyclopædia Britannica prefer the German spelling, and the local government uses the German spelling on their English webpages.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The English pronunciation, with stress on the first syllable, is applied to both the German and English spellings, which is different from German pronunciation, with stress on the second syllable and a long second vowel.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The traditional English spelling is still used in historical contexts, especially when referring to the British House of Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover was founded in medieval times on the east bank of the Leine River.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Its original name *Honovere* may mean 'high river bank', but that is debated.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover was a small village of ferrymen and fishermen that became a comparatively large town in the 13th century and received town privileges in 1241 because of its position at a natural crossroads.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] As overland travel was relatively difficult, its position on the upper navigable reaches of the river helped it grow from increasing trade.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It was connected to the Hanseatic League city of Bremen by the Leine River and was situated near the southern edge of the wide North German Plain and northwest of the Harz mountains, so east–west traffic such as mule trains passed through it.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover was thus a gateway to the Rhine, Ruhr and Saar river valleys, and their industrial areas which grew up to the southwest and the plains regions to the east and north for overland traffic skirting the Harz between the Low Countries and Saxony or Thuringia.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In the 14th century, the main churches of Hanover were built, as well as a city wall with three city gates.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The beginning of industrialization in Germany led to trade in iron and silver from the northern Harz Mountains, which increased the city's importance.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 1636 George, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg, ruler of the Brunswick-Lüneburg principality of Calenberg, moved his residence to Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Dukes of Brunswick-Lüneburg were elevated by the Holy Roman Emperor to the rank of Prince-Elector in 1692, which was confirmed by the Imperial Diet in 1708.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Thus, the principality was upgraded to the Electorate of Brunswick-Lüneburg, colloquially known as the Electorate of Hanover after Calenberg's capital (see also House of Hanover).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Its electors later became monarchs of Great Britain (and from 1801 of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The first of them was George I Louis, who acceded to the British throne in 1714.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The last British monarch who reigned in Hanover was William IV.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Semi-Salic law, which required succession by the male line if possible, forbade the accession of Queen Victoria in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] As a male-line descendant of George I, Queen Victoria was herself a member of the House of Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Her descendants, however, bore her husband's titular name of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Three kings of Great Britain, or the United Kingdom, were concurrently also Electoral Princes of Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] During the time of the personal union of the crowns of the United Kingdom and Hanover (1714–1837), the monarchs rarely visited the city.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In fact during the reigns of the last three joint rulers (1760–1837), there was only one short visit, by George IV in 1821.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] From 1816 to 1837, Viceroy Adolphus represented the monarch in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] During the Seven Years' War, the Battle of Hastenbeck was fought near the city on 26 July 1757.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The French army defeated the Hanoverian Army of Observation, which led to the city's occupation as part of the Invasion of Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It was recaptured by Anglo-German forces, led by Ferdinand of Brunswick, the following year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] After Napoleon imposed the Convention of Artlenburg (treaty of the Elbe) on 5 July 1803, about 35,000 French soldiers occupied Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The convention also required disbanding the Hanoverian Army.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] However, George III did not recognise the Convention of the Elbe, which resulted in a great number of soldiers from Hanover eventually emigrating to Great Britain, where the King's German Legion was formed.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It was only troops from Hanover and Brunswick who consistently opposed France throughout the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Legion later played an important role in the Peninsular War and the Battle of Waterloo in 1815.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 1814 the electorate became the Kingdom of Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 1837, the personal union of the United Kingdom and Hanover ended because William IV's heir in the United Kingdom was female (Queen Victoria).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover could be inherited only by male heirs.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Thus, Hanover passed to William IV's brother, Ernest Augustus, and remained a kingdom until 1866, when it was annexed by the Prussia during the Austro-Prussian war.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Though Hanover was expected to defeat Prussia at the Battle of Langensalza in 1866, Prussia employed Moltke the Elder's Kesselschlacht order of battle to destroy the Hanoverian Army.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Thereafter the city of Hanover became the capital of the Prussian Province of Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 1872, the first horse railway was inaugurated, and in 1893, an electric tram was installed.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] A local newspaper, the *Hannoverscher Kurier*, was published in Hanover at this time.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] After 1937 the lord mayor and the state commissioners of Hanover were members of the NSDAP (Nazi party).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] A large Jewish population then existed in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In October 1938, 484 Hanoverian Jews of Polish origin were expelled to Poland, including the Grynszpan family.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] However, Poland refused to accept them, leaving them stranded at the border with thousands of other Polish-Jewish deportees, fed only intermittently by the Polish Red Cross and Jewish welfare organisations.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Grynszpans' son Herschel Grynszpan was in Paris at the time.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] When he learned of what was happening, he drove to the German embassy in Paris and shot the German diplomat Eduard Ernst vom Rath, who died shortly afterwards.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Nazis took this act as a pretext to stage a nationwide pogrom known as Kristallnacht (9 November 1938).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] On that day, the synagogue of Hanover, designed in 1870 by Edwin Oppler in neo-romantic style, was burnt by the Nazis.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In September 1941, through the "Action Lauterbacher" plan, a ghettoisation of the remaining Hanoverian Jewish families began.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Even before the Wannsee Conference, on 15 December 1941, the first Jews from Hanover were deported to Riga.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] A total of 2,400 people were deported, and very few survived.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] During the war seven concentration camps were constructed in Hanover, in which many Jews were confined, but also Polish, French and Russian women.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Of the approximately 2271 Jews who had lived in Hanover in 1939, fewer than 100 were still in the city when troops of the United States Army arrived on 10 April 1945 to occupy Hanover at the end of the war.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Today, a memorial at the Opera Square is a reminder of the persecution of the Jews in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] After the war a large group of Orthodox Jewish survivors of the nearby Bergen-Belsen concentration camp settled in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] There was also a camp for Sinti and Romani people (see *Romani Holocaust*), and dozens of forced labour subcamps of the Stalag XI-B prisoner-of-war camp for Allied POWs.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] As an important railway and road junction and production centre, Hanover was a major target for strategic bombing during World War II, including the Oil Campaign.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Maschinenfabrik Niedersachsen* (Badenstedt).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Residential areas were also targeted, and more than 6,000 civilians were killed by the Allied bombing raids.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] More than 90% of the city centre was destroyed in a total of 88 bombing raids.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] After the war, the Aegidienkirche was not rebuilt and its ruins were left as a war memorial.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Today around 25% of the city consists of buildings from before 1950.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Allied ground advance into Germany reached Hanover in April 1945.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The US 84th Infantry Division captured the city on 10 April 1945.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover was in the British zone of occupation of Germany and became part of the new state (Land) of Lower Saxony in 1946.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 1947, Hanover established its relationship with Bristol, England in exchanges of goods, students and music.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] This would link the two cities as models for establishing programs and organizations like Sister Cities International.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Today Hanover is a vice-president city of Mayors for Peace, an international mayoral organisation mobilising cities and citizens worldwide to abolish and eliminate nuclear weapons by 2020.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*) independent of the isotherm.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Although the city is not on a coastal location, the predominant air masses are still from the ocean, unlike other places further east or south-central Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The city of Hanover is divided into 13 boroughs (*Stadtbezirke*) and 53 quarters (*Stadtteile*).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The current mayor of Hanover is Belit Onay of Alliance 90/The Greens, elected in 2019.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Hanover city council governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] There are around 5,500 buildings of major historic value within city limits.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] One of Hanover's most grandiose sights is the Royal Gardens of Herrenhausen.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Its Great Garden is an important European Baroque garden.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The palace itself was largely destroyed by Allied bombing, but was reconstructed and reopened in 2013.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Among its points of interest is the Grotto, with the interior designed by French artist Niki de Saint Phalle.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Great Garden consists of several parts and features Europe's tallest garden fountain.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The historic *Garden Theatre* has hosted the musicals of the German rock musician Heinz Rudolf Kunze.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Also at Herrenhausen, the *Berggarten* is a botanical garden with the most varied collection of orchids in Europe.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some points of interest are the *Tropical House*, the *Cactus House*, the *Canary House* and the *Orchid House*, and free-flying birds and butterflies.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Near the entrance to the Berggarten is the historic *Library Pavillon*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Mausoleum* of the Guelphs is also in the Berggarten.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Like the Great Garden, the Berggarten also consists of several parts, for example the *Paradies* and the *Prairie Garden*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Georgengarten* is an English landscape garden.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Leibniz Temple* and the *Georgen Palace* are two points of interest there.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The landmark of Hanover is the New Town Hall (*Neues Rathaus*).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Inside the building are four scale models of the city.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] An elevator ascends to the observation deck at the top of the large dome along a variable angle of up to 17 degrees, thought to be unique in the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Hanover Zoo* received the Park Scout Award for the fourth year running in 2009–10, placing it among the best zoos in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The zoo consists of several theme areas: Sambesi, Meyers Farm, Gorilla-Mountain, Jungle-Palace, and Mullewapp.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some smaller areas are Australia, the wooded area for wolves, and the so-called swimming area with many seabirds.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] There is also a tropical house, a jungle house, and a show arena.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The new Canadian-themed area, Yukon Bay, opened in 2010.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 2010 the Hanover Zoo had over 1.6 million visitors.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] There is also the *Sea Life Centre Hanover*, which is the first tropical aquarium in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Another point of interest is the *Old Town*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In the centre are the large *Marktkirche* (Church *St.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Georgii et Jacobi*, preaching venue of the bishop of the Lutheran Landeskirche Hanovers), and the 15th century *Old Town Hall*, heavily damaged by Allied bombing in 1943, and reconstructed after World War II.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Nearby are the *Leibniz House*, the *Nolte House*, and the *Beguine Tower*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Kreuz-Church-Quarter* around the *Kreuz Church* contains many little lanes.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Nearby is the old royal sports hall, now called the *Ballhof* theatre.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] On the edge of the Old Town are the *Market Hall*, the *Leine Palace*, and the ruin of the *Aegidien Church* which is now a monument to the victims of war and violence.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Through the *Marstall Gate* the bank of the river *Leine* can be reached; the *Nanas* of Niki de Saint Phalle are there.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] They are part of the *Sculpture Mile*, which starts at *Trammplatz*, runs along the river bank, crosses *Königsworther Square*, and ends at the entrance of the *Georgengarten*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Near the Old Town is the district of Calenberger Neustadt where the Catholic St.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Clement's Basilica, the *Reformed Church* and the Lutheran Neustädter Hof- und Stadtkirche St.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Gehry), the specially designed *Bus Stops*, the *Opera House*, the *Hanover Central Station*, the *Maschsee* lake and the city forest *Eilenriede*, which is one of the largest of its kind in Europe.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] For recreation, Hanover has 40 parks, forests and gardens, a couple of lakes, two rivers and a canal.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The historic *Leibniz Letters*, which can be viewed in the *Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Library*, have been on UNESCO's Memory of the World Register since 2007.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Outside the city centre is the *Hanover Fairground*, which was the site of EXPO 2000 fair.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some points of interest are the *Planet M.*, the former *German Pavillon*, some nations' vacant pavilions, the *Expowale*, the *EXPO-Plaza* and the *EXPO-Gardens* (Parc Agricole, EXPO-Park South and the Gardens of change).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The fairground can be reached by the *Exponale*, one of the largest pedestrian bridges in Europe.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Hanover Fairground* is the largest exhibition centre in the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It provides 496,000 square metres (5.34 million square feet) of covered indoor space, 58,000 square metres (620 thousand square feet) of open-air space, 27 halls and pavilions.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Many of the Exhibition Centre's halls are architectural highlights.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Furthermore, it offers the Convention Center with its 35 function rooms, glassed-in areas between halls, grassy park-like recreation zones and its own heliport.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Two important sights on the fairground are the *Hermes Tower* (88.8 metres or 291 feet high) and the *EXPO Roof*, the largest wooden roof in the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In the district of Anderten is the *European Cheese Centre*, termed a "Cheese Experience Centre." Another tourist sight in Anderten is the *Hindenburg Lock*, which was the biggest lock in Europe when it was constructed in 1928.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Tiergarten* in the district of Kirchrode is a forest originally used for deer and other game for the king's table.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The 282-metre-high (925 ft) *Telemax* communications tower, the tallest building in Lower Saxony and the highest television tower in northern Germany, lies in the district of Groß-Buchholz.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some other notable towers are the *VW-Tower* in the city centre and the old towers of the former middle-age defence belt: *Döhrener Tower*, *Lister Tower* and the *Horse Tower*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The 36 most significant sights of the city centre are connected by a 4.2-kilometre-long (3 mi) walking trail called the *Red Thread* that is literally painted onto the pavement with red paint.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It starts at the Tourist Information Office and ends on the Ernst-August-Square, both in front of the central train station.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] There is also a guided sightseeing bus tour through the city.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover has a population of about 540,000.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It is the largest city in Lower Saxony and is the 13th largest city in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Hanover Region, a district that surrounds the city of Hanover and cities like Langenhagen, Garbsen and Laatzen has a population of about 1,160,000 and is the largest District (Landkreis) in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover metropolitan region, which includes also cities like Braunschweig, Hildesheim and Göttingen, has a population of about 3,850,000 and is the 8th largest metropolitan area in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover passed a population of 100,000 in 1875, and Hanover's population has grown since 1946, when Hanover became the capital of Lower Saxony state and it grew rapidly in 1950s and 60s due to West German Wirtschaftswunder.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] This also saw the growth of a large migrant population, drawn largely from Turkey, Greece and Italy.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover has also one of the largest Vietnamese communities in former West Germany due to its proximity to former East Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Viên Giác pagoda in Mittelfeld, southern district of Hanover is the largest Vietnamese pagoda in Germany and one of the largest in Europe.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover is one of the liveable cities due to its good location and good population size.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It is the fifth-largest city in the Low German dialect area after Hamburg, Dortmund, Essen and Bremen.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover is headquarters for several Protestant organizations, including the World Communion of Reformed Churches, the Protestant Church in Germany, the Reformed Alliance, the United Evangelical Lutheran Church of Germany, and the Independent Evangelical-Lutheran Church.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 2015, 31.1% of the population were Protestant and 13.4% were Roman Catholic.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The majority 55.5% were irreligious or other religion.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Historisches Museum Hanover (Historic museum) describes the history of Hanover, from the medieval settlement "Honovere" to the city of today.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The museum focuses on the period from 1714 to 1834 when Hanover had a strong relationship with the British royal family of that period.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] With more than 4,000 members, the Kestnergesellschaft is the largest art society in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The museum hosts exhibitions from classical modernist art to contemporary art.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Emphasis is placed on film, video, contemporary music and architecture, room installments and presentations of contemporary paintings, sculptures and video art.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Kestner-Museum is located in the *House of 5,000 windows*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The museum is named after August Kestner and exhibits 6,000 years of applied art in four areas: Ancient cultures, ancient Egypt, applied art and a valuable collection of historic coins.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The KUBUS is a forum for contemporary art.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It features mostly exhibitions and projects of artists from Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Kunstverein Hannover (Art Society Hanover) shows contemporary art and was established in 1832 as one of the first art societies in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It is located in the *Künstlerhaus* (House of artists).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] There are around seven international exhibitions each year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Landesmuseum Hanover is the largest museum in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The art gallery shows European art from the 11th to the 20th century, the nature department shows the zoology, geology, botanic, geology and a *vivarium* with fish, insects, reptiles and amphibians.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The primeval department shows the primeval history of Lower Saxony, and the folklore department shows cultures from all over the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Sprengel Museum shows the art of the 20th century.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It is one of the most notable art museums in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The focus is put on the classical modernist art with the collection of *Kurt Schwitters*, works of German expressionism, and French cubism, the cabinet of abstracts, the graphics and the department of photography and media.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Furthermore, the museum shows the works of the French artist Niki de Saint-Phalle.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Theatre Museum shows an exhibition of the history of the theatre in Hanover from the 17th century up to now: opera, concert, drama and ballet.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The museum also hosts several touring exhibitions during the year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Wilhelm Busch Museum is the *German Museum of Caricature and Critical Graphic Arts*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The collection of the works of Wilhelm Busch and the extensive collection of cartoons and critical graphics is unique in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Furthermore, the museum hosts several exhibitions of national and international artists during the year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] A cabinet of coins is the Münzkabinett der TUI-AG.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Polizeigeschichtliche Sammlung Niedersachsen* is the largest police museum in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Textiles from all over the world can be visited in the *Museum for textile art*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *EXPOseeum* is the museum of the world-exhibition "EXPO 2000 Hanover".
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Carpets and objects from the orient can be visited in the *Oriental Carpet Museum*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Museum for the visually impaired* is a rarity in Germany, there is only one other of its kind in Berlin.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Museum of veterinary medicine* is unique in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Museum for Energy History* describes the 150 years old history of the application of energy.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Heimat-Museum Ahlem* shows the history of the district of Ahlem.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Mahn- und Gedenkstätte Ahlem* describes the history of the Jewish people in Hanover and the *Stiftung Ahlers Pro Arte / Kestner Pro Arte* shows modern art.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Modern art is also the main topic of the *Kunsthalle Faust*, the *Nord/LB Art Gallery* and of the *Foro Artistico / Eisfabrik*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some leading art events in Hanover are the *Long Night of the Museums* and the *Zinnober Kunstvolkslauf* which features all the galleries in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] People who are interested in astronomy should visit the *Observatory Geschwister Herschel* on the Lindener Mountain or the small planetarium inside of the Bismarck School.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Around 40 theatres are located in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Opera House*, the *Schauspielhaus* (Play House), the *Ballhof eins*, the *Ballhof zwei* and the *Cumberlandsche Galerie* belong to the *Lower Saxony State Theatre*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Theater am Aegi is Hanover's principal theatre for musicals, shows and guest performances.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Neues Theater* (New Theatre) is the boulevard theatre of Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Theater für Niedersachsen* is another large theatre in Hanover, which also has an own musical company.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some of the most important musical productions are the rock musicals of the German rock musician Heinz Rudolph Kunze, which take place at the *Garden-Theatre* in the Great Garden.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some important theatre events are the *Tanztheater International*, the *Long Night of the Theatres*, the *Festival Theaterformen* and the *International Competition for Choreographers*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover's leading cabaret stage is the *GOP Variety theatre* which is located in the *Georgs Palace*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some other cabaret-stages are the *Variety Marlene*, the *Uhu-Theatre*. the theatre *Die Hinterbühne*, the *Rampenlich Variety* and the revue-stage *TAK*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The most important cabaret event is the *Kleines Fest im Großen Garten* (Little Festival in the Great Garden) which is the most successful cabaret festival in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It features artists from around the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some other important events are the *Calenberger Cabaret Weeks*, the *Hanover Cabaret Festival* and the *Wintervariety*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover has two symphony orchestras: The Lower Saxon State Orchestra Hanover and the NDR Radiophilharmonie (North German Radio Philharmonic Orchestra).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Two notable choirs have their homes in Hanover: the Mädchenchor Hanover (girls' choir) and the Knabenchor Hanover (boys' choir).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The rock bands Scorpions and Fury in the Slaughterhouse are originally from Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Acclaimed DJ Mousse T also has his main recording studio in the area.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Jordan, member of the band Scooter was born here in 1968.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Lena, winner of the 2010 Eurovision Song Contest, is also from Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover 96 (nicknamed *Die Roten*, literally 'the Reds') is the top local football team that currently plays in the 2.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Home games are played at the Niedersachsenstadion (*Lower Saxony Stadium*), which hosted matches in the 1974 and 2006 World Cups and the Euro 1988.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Their reserve team Hanover 96 II plays in the 3rd division of German Football.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Their home games were played in the traditional Eilenriedestadion until they moved to the HDI Arena due to DFL directives.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Arminia Hanover is another traditional football team in Hanover that has played in the second division (then 2.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Liga Nord) for years and plays now in the Niedersachsen-West Liga (Lower Saxony League West).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Home matches are played in the Rudolf-Kalweit-Stadium.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Hanover Indians are the local ice hockey team.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Their home games are played at the traditional Eisstadion am Pferdeturm.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Hanover Scorpions played in Hanover in Germany's top league until 2013 when they sold their license and moved to Langenhagen.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover was one of the rugby union capitals in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The first German rugby team was founded in Hanover in 1878.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover-based teams dominated the German rugby scene for a long time.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] DSV 78 Hanover, SC Germania List, and SV Odin Hanover plays in the first division, and DRC Hanover as well as SG 78/08 Hanover play in the second division.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover has traditionally been one of Germany's hubs in Water sports and especially in Water polo.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The SG Waspo'98 Hanover won the Deutsche Wasserball-Liga in 2020 and 2021.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In total, clubs from Hanover have won the German championship 11 times.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Thanks to the Maschsee lake, the rivers Ihme and Leine and to the Mittellandkanal canal, Hanover hosts sailing schools, yacht schools, waterski clubs, rowing clubs, canoe clubs and paddle clubs.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The first German fencing club was founded in Hanover in 1862.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Today there are three additional fencing clubs in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Hanover Korbjäger are the city's top basketball team.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] They play their home games at the IGS Linden.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Hanover Regents play in the third Bundesliga (baseball) division.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Hanover Grizzlies, Armina Spartans and Hanover Stampeders are the local American football teams.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Hanover Marathon is the biggest running event in Hanover with more than 11,000 participants and usually around 200,000 spectators.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some other important running events are the Gilde Stadtstaffel (a relay event), the Sport-Check Nachtlauf (a night running event), the "Herrenhäuser Team-Challenge", the "Hannoversche Firmenlauf" (a company running event) and the Silvesterlauf (New Year's running event).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover also hosts an important international cycle race, the "*Nacht von Hannover"* ("Night of Hanover").
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The race takes place around the market hall.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The lake Maschsee hosts international dragon boat races and canoe olo tournaments.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Many regattas take place during the year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] "Head of the river Leine" on the river Leine is one of the biggest rowing regattas in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] One of Germany's most successful dragon boat teams, the All Sports Team Hanover, which has won since its foundation in year 2000 more than 100 medals on national and international competitions, regularly trains on the local Maschsee lake.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some other important sport events include the Lower Saxony beach volleyball tournament, the international horse show "German Classics" and the international ice hockey tournament Nations Cup.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover is one of the leading exhibition cities in the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It hosts more than 60 international and national exhibitions every year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The most popular ones are the *CeBIT*, the *Hanover Fair*, the *Domotex*, the *Ligna*, the *IAA Nutzfahrzeuge* and the *Agritechnica*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover is also host to the *Schützenfest Hannover,* the largest marksmen's fun fair in the world which takes place once a year from late June to early July.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Founded in 1529, it consists of more than 260 rides and inns, five large beer tents and a large entertainment programme.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The highlight of this fun fair is the 12-kilometre-long (7 mi) *Parade of the Marksmen* with more than 12,000 participants from all over the world, including around 5,000 marksmen, 128 bands, and more than 70 wagons, carriages, and other festival vehicles.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] This makes it the longest procession in Europe.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Around 2 million people visit this fun fair every year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The landmark of this event is one of the largest transportable Ferris wheels in the world, with a height of about 60 metres (197 ft).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover also hosts one of the two largest spring festivals in Europe, with around 180 rides and inns, 2 large beer tents, and around 1.5 million visitors each year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Oktoberfest Hanover is the second largest Oktoberfest in the world with around 160 rides and inns, two large beer tents and around 1 million visitors each year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Maschsee Festival* takes place around the Maschsee Lake.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Each year around 2 million visitors come to enjoy live music, comedy, cabaret, and much more.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It is the largest Volksfest of its kind in Northern Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Great Garden hosts every year the *International Fireworks Competition*, and the *International Festival Weeks Herrenhausen,* with music and cabaret performances.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Carnival Procession* is around 3 kilometres (2 mi) long and consists of 3,000 participants, around 30 festival vehicles and around 20 bands and takes place every year.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover also hosts food-oriented festivals including the *Wine Festival* and the *Gourmet Festival*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It also hosts some special markets like the *Old Town Flea Market* and the *Market for Art and Trade*.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Some other major markets include the *Christmas Markets of the City of Hanover* in the Old Town and city centre, and the Lister Meile.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover is an attractive tourist place due to its many sights and famous events.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover had about 580,000 visitors in 2021, predominantly from the Netherlands and the United Kingdom.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Famous sights in Hanover are New Town Hall, Herrenhausen Gardens and Hanover Zoo, which is one of the largest zoos in Germany.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The annual trade fair "Hannover Messe" usually attracts between 100,000 and 200,000 visitors.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] First held in 1947, it is dedicated to the topic of industry development and is one of the world's largest trade fairs.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The city's central station, Hanover Hauptbahnhof, is a hub of the German high-speed ICE network.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It is the starting point of the Hanover-Würzburg high-speed rail line and also the central hub for the Hanover S-Bahn.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] It offers many international and national connections.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover and its area is served by Hanover Airport (IATA code: HAJ; ICAO code: EDDV) in Langenhagen.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover is also an important hub of Germany's autobahn network; the junction of two major autobahns, the A 2 and A 7 is at *Kreuz Hanover-Ost*, at the northeastern edge of the city.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Local autobahns are A 352 (a shortcut between A 7 and A 2, also known as the *Airport autobahn* because it passes Hanover Airport), and the A 37.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The expressway (*Schnellweg*) system, a number of Bundesstraße roads, forms a structure loosely resembling a large ring road together with A 2 and A 7.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover has an extensive Stadtbahn and bus system, operated by üstra.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The city uses designer buses and tramways, the TW 6000 and TW 2000 trams being examples.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Bicycle paths are very common in the city centre.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] At off-peak hours bikes can be taken on a tram or bus.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Various industrial businesses are located in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Volkswagen Commercial Vehicles Transporter (VWN) factory at Hanover-Stöcken is the biggest employer in the region and operates a large plant at the northern edge of town adjoining the canal Mittellandkanal and the autobahn A 2.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Volkswagen shares a coal-burning power plant with a factory of German tire and automobile parts manufacturer Continental AG.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Continental, founded in Hanover in 1871, is one of the city's major companies.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Since 2008 a take-over has been in progress: the Schaeffler Group from Herzogenaurach (Bavaria) holds the majority of Continental's stock but were required due to the financial crisis to deposit the options as securities at banks.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The audio equipment company Sennheiser and the travel group TUI AG are both based in Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hanover is home to many insurance companies including Talanx, VHV Group, and Concordia Insurance.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The major global reinsurance company Hannover Re also has its headquarters east of the city centre.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 2012, the city generated a GDP of €29.5 billion, which is equivalent to €74,822 per employee.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The gross value of production in 2012 was €26.4 billion, which is equivalent to €66,822 per employee.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Around 300,000 employees were counted in 2014.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Of these, 189,000 had their primary residence in Hanover, while 164,892 commute into the city every day.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] In 2014 the city was home to 34,198 businesses, of which 9,342 were registered in the German Trade Register and 24,856 counted as small businesses.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hence, more than half of the metropolitan area's businesses in the German Trade Register are located in Hanover (17,485 total).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hannoverimpuls GMBH is a joint business development company from the city and region of Hanover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The company was founded in 2003 and supports the start-up, growth and relocation of businesses in the Hanover Region.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The focus is on thirteen sectors, which stand for sustainable economic growth: Automotive, Energy Solutions, Information and Communications Technology, Life Sciences, Optical Technologies, Creative Industries and Production Engineering.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] A range of programmes supports companies from the key industries in their expansion plans in Hanover or abroad.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Three regional centres specifically promote international economic relations with Russia, India and Turkey.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Institut für Integrierte Produktion Hannover is a spin-off from Leibniz University Hanover in the field of production technology that promotes transfer of scientific knowledge to business.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The Leibniz University Hanover is the largest funded institution in Hanover for providing higher education to students from around the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Below are the names of the universities and some of the important schools, including newly opened Hannover Medical Research School in 2003 for attracting the students from biology background from around the world.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The *Schulbiologiezentrum Hannover* maintains practical biology schools in four locations (Botanischer Schulgarten Burg, Freiluftschule Burg, Zooschule Hannover, and Botanischer Schulgarten Linden).
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] The University of Veterinary Medicine Hanover also maintains its own botanical garden specializing in medicinal and poisonous plants, the Heil- und Giftpflanzengarten der Tierärztlichen Hochschule Hannover.
[src:emo-trade-show/hanover-p01] Hannover has several vocational schools like Berufsbildende Schulen (BBS) ME - Metalltechnik und Elektrotechnik, which specializes in metal and electrical engineering, and BBS Cora Berliner, which specializes in business administration as well as the leisure and trading industries.
[src:emo-trade-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] The **International Manufacturing Technology Show** (**IMTS**), first held in Cleveland, Ohio in 1927 , is a trade show that features industrial machinery and technology.
[src:emo-trade-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] It is the largest manufacturing technology trade show in North America, and in 1990 was renamed from the original "International Machine Tool Show" to reflect the growing scope of the show to additional technologies such as welding, lubrication, and materials engineering.
[src:emo-trade-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] The show is managed by the Association for Manufacturing Technology.
[src:emo-trade-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] The six-day show is held in even-numbered years at Chicago's McCormick Place and draws attendees and exhibitors from the U.S. and some 119 other countries.
[src:emo-trade-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] IMTS was cancelled in 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic, but reconvened for 2022.
[src:emo-trade-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] For 2018, there were 129,415 registrants and 2,563 exhibitors across four buildings and 1,424,232 square feet (132,315.5 m2) of exhibit space.
[src:emo-trade-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] Since 2004, IMTS has sponsored the Emerging Technology Center, where the latest academic and industrial advancements are showcased.
[src:emo-trade-show/international-manufacturing-technology-show] IMTS 2012, for example, featured a Local Motors Rally Fighter car built live on the show floor, MTConnect, the open-source communication and interconnectivity standard, and MT*Insight*, the game-changing customized manufacturing business intelligence system.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] A **machine tool** is a machine for handling or machining metal or other rigid materials, usually by cutting, boring, grinding, shearing, or other forms of deformations.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Machine tools employ some sort of tool that does the cutting or shaping.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] All machine tools have some means of constraining the workpiece and provide a guided movement of the parts of the machine.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Thus, the relative movement between the workpiece and the cutting tool (which is called the **toolpath**) is controlled or constrained by the machine to at least some extent, rather than being entirely "offhand" or "freehand".
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] It is a power-driven metal cutting machine which assists in managing the needed relative motion between cutting tool and the job that changes the size and shape of the job material.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The precise definition of the term *machine tool* varies among users.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] While all machine tools are "machines that help people to make things", not all factory machines are machine tools.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Today machine tools are typically powered other than by the human muscle (e.g., electrically, hydraulically, or via line shaft), used to make manufactured parts (components) in various ways that include cutting or certain other kinds of deformation.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] With their inherent precision, machine tools enabled the economical production of interchangeable parts.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] In this view of the definition, the term, arising at a time when all tools up till then had been hand tools, simply provided a label for "tools that were machines instead of hand tools".
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] This lathe "produced screw threads out of wood and employed a true compound slide rest".
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] National Bureau of Economic Research (NBER) referenced the definition of a machine tool as "any machine operating by other than hand power which employs a tool to work on metal".
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The narrowest colloquial sense of the term reserves it only for machines that perform metal cutting—in other words, the many kinds of conventional machining and grinding.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] These processes are a type of deformation that produces swarf.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] However, economists use a slightly broader sense that also includes metal deformation of other types that squeeze the metal into shape without cutting off swarf, such as rolling, stamping with dies, shearing, swaging, riveting, and others.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Thus presses are usually included in the economic definition of machine tools.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Many reports on machine tool export and import and similar economic topics use this broader definition.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The colloquial sense implying conventional metal cutting is also growing obsolete because of changing technology over the decades.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] In addition, some of the newly developed additive manufacturing processes, which are not about cutting away material but rather about adding it, are done by machines that are likely to end up labeled, in some cases, as machine tools.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] In fact, machine tool builders are already developing machines that include both subtractive and additive manufacturing in one work envelope, and retrofits of existing machines are underway.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] In modern precision engineering, the accuracy of machine tool components is often maintained through the use of a Hirth joint.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] This coupling is the industry standard for high-accuracy positioning in components such as CNC rotary tables and tool turrets.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Its straight-tooth geometry provides maximum static stiffness and positional repeatability, ensuring that the machine maintains micron-level alignment while resisting heavy cutting forces during the machining process.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Forerunners of machine tools included bow drills and potter's wheels, which had existed in ancient Egypt prior to 2500 BC, and lathes, known to have existed in multiple regions of Europe since at least 1000 to 500 BC.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] But it was not until the later Middle Ages and the Age of Enlightenment that the modern concept of a machine tool—a class of machines used as tools in the making of metal parts, and incorporating machine-guided toolpath—began to evolve.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Clockmakers of the Middle Ages and renaissance men such as Leonardo da Vinci helped expand humans' technological milieu toward the preconditions for industrial machine tools.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] During the 18th and 19th centuries, and even in many cases in the 20th, the builders of machine tools tended to be the same people who would then use them to produce the end products (manufactured goods).
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] However, from these roots also evolved an industry of machine tool builders as we define them today, meaning people who specialize in building machine tools for sale to others.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Historians of machine tools often focus on a handful of major industries that most spurred machine tool development.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Others could be included in this list as well, but they tend to be connected with the root causes already listed.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Machine tools filled a need created by textile machinery during the Industrial Revolution in England in the middle to late 1700s.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Until that time, machinery was made mostly from wood, often including gearing and shafts.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The increase in mechanization required more metal parts, which were usually made of cast iron or wrought iron.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Cast iron could be cast in molds for larger parts, such as engine cylinders and gears, but was difficult to work with a file and could not be hammered.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Red hot wrought iron could be hammered into shapes.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Room temperature wrought iron was worked with a file and chisel and could be made into gears and other complex parts; however, hand working lacked precision and was a slow and expensive process.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] James Watt was unable to have an accurately bored cylinder for his first steam engine, trying for several years until John Wilkinson invented a suitable boring machine in 1774, boring Boulton & Watt's first commercial engine in 1776.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The advance in the accuracy of machine tools can be traced to Henry Maudslay and refined by Joseph Whitworth.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The process by which the master plane gages were produced dates back to antiquity but was refined to an unprecedented degree in the Maudslay shop.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The process begins with three square plates each given an identification (ex., 1,2 and 3).
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The first step is to rub plates 1 and 2 together with a marking medium (called bluing today) revealing the high spots which would be removed by hand scraping with a steel scraper, until no irregularities were visible.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] This would not produce true plane surfaces but a "ball and socket" concave-concave and convex-convex fit, as this mechanical fit, like two perfect planes, can slide over each other and reveal no high spots.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The rubbing and marking are repeated after rotating 2 relative to 1 by 90 degrees to eliminate concave-convex "potato-chip" curvature.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Next, plate number 3 is compared and scraped to conform to plate number 1 in the same two trials.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] In this manner plates number 2 and 3 would be identical.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Next plates number 2 and 3 would be checked against each other to determine what condition existed, either both plates were "balls" or "sockets" or "chips" or a combination.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] These would then be scraped until no high spots existed and then compared to plate number 1.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Repeating this process of comparing and scraping the three plates could produce plane surfaces accurate to within millionths of an inch (the thickness of the marking medium).
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The traditional method of producing the surface gages used an abrasive powder rubbed between the plates to remove the high spots, but it was Whitworth who contributed the refinement of replacing the grinding with hand scraping.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Sometime after 1825, Whitworth went to work for Maudslay and it was there that Whitworth perfected the hand scraping of master surface plane gages.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] With the creation of master plane gages of such high accuracy, all critical components of machine tools (i.e., guiding surfaces such as machine ways) could then be compared against them and scraped to the desired accuracy.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The first machine tools offered for sale (i.e., commercially available) were constructed by Matthew Murray in England around 1800.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Others, such as Henry Maudslay, James Nasmyth, and Joseph Whitworth, soon followed the path of expanding their entrepreneurship from manufactured end products and millwright work into the realm of building machine tools for sale.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Important early machine tools included the slide rest lathe, screw-cutting lathe, turret lathe, milling machine, pattern tracing lathe, shaper, and metal planer, which were all in use before 1840.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] With these machine tools the decades-old objective of producing interchangeable parts was finally realized.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] An important early example of something now taken for granted was the standardization of screw fasteners such as nuts and bolts.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Before about the beginning of the 19th century, these were used in pairs, and even screws of the same machine were generally not interchangeable.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Methods were developed to cut screw thread to a greater precision than that of the feed screw in the lathe being used.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] This led to the bar length standards of the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] American production of machine tools was a critical factor in the Allies' victory in World War II.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Production of machine tools tripled in the United States in the war.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] No war was more industrialized than World War II, and it has been written that the war was won as much by machine shops as by machine guns.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The production of machine tools is concentrated in about 10 countries worldwide: China, Japan, Germany, Italy, South Korea, Taiwan, Switzerland, US, Austria, Spain and a few others.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Machine tool innovation continues in several public and private research centers worldwide.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Machine tools can be powered from a variety of sources.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Human and animal power (via cranks, treadles, treadmills, or treadwheels) were used in the past, as was water power (via water wheel); however, following the development of high-pressure steam engines in the mid 19th century, factories increasingly used steam power.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Factories also used hydraulic and pneumatic power.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Many small workshops continued to use water, human and animal power until electrification after 1900.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Today most machine tools are powered by electricity; hydraulic and pneumatic power are sometimes used, but this is uncommon.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Machine tools can be operated manually, or under automatic control.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Early machines used flywheels to stabilize their motion and had complex systems of gears and levers to control the machine and the piece being worked on.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Soon after World War II, the numerical control (NC) machine was developed.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] NC machines used a series of numbers punched on paper tape or punched cards to control their motion.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] In the 1960s, computers were added to give even more flexibility to the process.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Such machines became known as computerized numerical control (CNC) machines.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] NC and CNC machines could precisely repeat sequences over and over, and could produce much more complex pieces than even the most skilled tool operators.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Before long, the machines could automatically change the specific cutting and shaping tools that were being used.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] For example, a drill machine might contain a magazine with a variety of drill bits for producing holes of various sizes.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Previously, either machine operators would usually have to manually change the bit or move the work piece to another station to perform these different operations.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The next logical step was to combine several different machine tools together, all under computer control.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] These are known as machining centers, and have dramatically changed the way parts are made.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] When fabricating or shaping parts, several techniques are used to remove unwanted metal.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Other techniques are used to *add* desired material.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] Devices that fabricate components by selective *addition* of material are called rapid prototyping machines.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The worldwide market for machine tools was approximately $81 billion in production in 2014 according to a survey by market research firm Gardner Research.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] The largest producer of machine tools was China with $23.8 billion of production followed by Germany and Japan at neck and neck with $12.9 billion and $12.88 billion respectively.
[src:emo-trade-show/machine-tool] South Korea and Italy rounded out the top 5 producers with revenue of $5.6 billion and $5 billion respectively.
